name: dec-3-enoic acid
Reason: The basic unit for comparison here could be octanoic acid, which has a melting point of 16°C. Octanoic acid is a saturated fatty acid, similar in molecular weight to the target dec-3-enoic acid, but without the double bond or the shift in the chain length. The double bond in dec-3-enoic acid introduces a kink in the molecular shape, which makes it pack less efficiently in the solid state, thus slightly lowering the melting point from what it would be if the compound was fully saturated. Additionally, the carboxyl group tends to increase the melting point because of the potential for hydrogen bonding. However, because dec-3-enoic acid has a longer carbon chain than octanoic acid, we might expect a slightly higher melting point due to increased van der Waals interactions. These competing factors will be considered in the prediction: -1°C for the double bond and +3°C for the longer carbon chain.
